Floor breakers.

A floor breaker is, in essence, a platform that only ever lays an air tile — a single-tile hole punched in the floor. Where a plain platform paints a tile you walk on, a floor breaker paints one tile of empty space the player falls through, so dropping one onto solid ground turns that tile into a gap. The difference from simply painting an air tile yourself is the sound: a floor breaker announces itself with a breaking sound the moment it appears and a second sound when it's removed, which is what makes it a trap rather than just a quiet hole. See the platforms topic for how the air tile behaves in general.

How a floor breaker works.

A floor breaker sits at a single tile and lays an air tile there — a spot with no footing that the player falls through instead of standing on. As it spawns it plays its breaking sound from that tile, so a floor breaker dropped onto an existing floor reads as the ground giving way underfoot. When the floor breaker is removed, it plays its removal sound from the same spot. On 3d maps the breaker sits at its given height. Because it's a single air tile, a floor breaker covers exactly one tile; to break a wider stretch of floor, place several side by side.

Floor breaker fields.

The floor breaker form takes the following:

Coordinates. An x and a y (and a z on 3d maps) — the single tile whose floor is broken.

Floor breaker sound (a folder name from the floor breaker sounds list, or none). The audio theme; the bundle supplies the spawn clip played as the floor breaks and the remove clip played when it's taken away. Pick none for a silent floor breaker.

Auditioning sounds in the builder.

While the floor breaker sound list is focused in the form, press space to hear the highlighted theme's breaking clip.

Authoring floor breakers by hand.

If you edit main.sif directly, a floor breaker is written under the name floor_breaker: floor_breaker x y breakertype. On 3d maps a z follows the y: floor_breaker x y z breakertype. The floor breaker sound must match a floor breaker sounds folder name or the word none.
